[[File:LORENZJ.jpg|thumb|right|200px]]
'''František Lorenz''' (24 December 1872 &ndash; 24 May 1957) also known as '''Francisco Valdomiro Lorenz''' or Francisco Lorenz was a Czech-born [[Polyglot (person)|polyglot]] and [[philosopher]] born in [[Zbyslav]] (nowadays part of the [[Czech Republic]]). He was one of the first [[Esperantists]] in the world, and was able to communicate in over 100 different languages. In 1891, Lorenz moved to [[Brazil]] due to political reasons.{{clarify|date=August 2017}} In Brazil, he lived firstly in [[Rio de Janeiro]], and then in [[Rio Grande do Sul]] ([[Southern Brazil]]). Lorenz published over 36 books in 40 languages and was one of the most prominent promoters of [[Esperanto movement]] ever in Brazil.<ref>[[Joan Francés Blanc]], "O Lorencovi", in František Vladimír Lorenc, ''[http://edicions.talvera.free.fr/bastidas/Franti%9aek%20Vladim%edr%20LORENC.%20Uplna%20ucebnice%20mezinarodniho%20reci%20dra%20Esperanta.pdf Úplná učebnice mezinárodní řeči dra. Esperanta]'', Edicions Talvera, Vert-Saint-Denis, 2012, {{ISBN|979-10-90696-20-4}}</ref> He died in [[Dom Feliciano]] (Brazil) in 1957.

