'''Running economy''' consists of many [[physiology|physiological]] and [[biomechanics|biomechanical]] factors that contribute to running performance, and is measured to quantify [[energy homeostasis|energy utilization]] while running at an [[aerobic exercise|aerobic]] intensity.<ref name="DRF_Daniels">{{cite book |last=Daniels |first1=Jack |authorlink=Jack Daniels (coach) |title=Daniels' Running Formula |chapter=Aerobic and training profiles |edition=3 |editor-last=Hanlon |editor-first=Tom |editor-link=Tom Hanlon |editor2-last=Marty |editor2-first=Claire |editor3-last=Wolpert |editor3-first=Tyler |location=Champaign, IL |publisher=Human Kinetics |date=31 Dec 2013 |pages=33–38 |isbn=978-1450431835 |quote=The measure of energy expended while running aerobically at some submax speeds is a measure of running economy. }}</ref>{{rp|33}}<ref name="FAR_Saunders">{{cite journal |title=Factor affecting running economy in trained distance runners |journal=Sports Medicine |year=2004 |last=Saunders |first=Philo |last2=Pyne |first2=David |last3=Telford |first3=Richard |last4=Hawley |first4=John |volume=34 |issue=7 |pages=465–485 |pmid=15233599 |url=http://www.siuaps.univ-rennes1.fr/digitalAssets/312/312102_Saunders_et_al.__2004_._Running_economy__Review___1_.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2014-08-18 |quote=Running economy (RE) is typically defined as the energy demand for a given velocity of submaximal running, and is determined by measuring the steady-state consumption of oxygen (VO<sub>2</sub>) and the respiratory exchange ratio. |doi=10.2165/00007256-200434070-00005 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821125357/http://www.siuaps.univ-rennes1.fr/digitalAssets/312/312102_Saunders_et_al.__2004_._Running_economy__Review___1_.pdf |archivedate=2014-08-21 |df= }}</ref>{{rp|465}}<ref name="TOM_Crowther">{{cite web |url=http://faculty.washington.edu/crowther/Misc/RBC/economy.shtml |title=Tips on maximizing your running economy |last=Crowther |first=Greg |work=Greg Crowther professional website |date=2001 |accessdate=2014-08-20 |quote=Measuring someone's running economy is equivalent to asking the question, "How far can this person run using a given amount of energy?" Energy use is usually reported in terms of oxygen consumption; the farther the person can run per unit of oxygen consumed -- or, stated another way, the less oxygen he/she consumes in running a given distance -- the more economical he/she is. }}</ref> [[Respirometry|Oxygen consumption]] (VO<sub>2</sub>) is the most direct method for measuring running economy, as the exchange of gases in the body, specifically oxygen and carbon dioxide, closely reflects energy metabolism. Those who are able to consume less oxygen while running at a given velocity are said to have a better running economy.

In [[distance running]], an athlete may attempt to improve performance through training designed to improve running economy. Running economy has been found to be a good predictor of race performance; it has been found to be a stronger correlate of performance than maximal oxygen uptake ([[VO2max|VO<sub>2</sub> max]]) in trained runners with the same values (Saunders, 2004). The literature relating to RE is vast and the determinants of RE supported by empirical data.

==Factors affecting running economy==
In ''The Lore of Running'', [[Tim Noakes]], a professor of exercise and sports science at the [[University of Cape Town]], and also recreational runner, describes a number of variables that may affect running economy: vertical motion while running, the ability of the muscles to absorb energy during the shock of landing and transfer it to push-off, [[biomechanics|biomechanical factors]], technique and type of activity, fitness and training, age, [[fatigue (medical)|fatigue]], [[gender]], [[Race (classification of human beings)|race]], weight of clothing and shoes, and environmental conditions.<ref name="Noakes">Noakes, Tim. 2003. ''The Lore of Running.'' (4th edition) [[Oxford University Press]] {{ISBN|0-87322-959-2}}</ref>

Various studies have shown [[marathon|marathon runners]] to be more economical than [[middle distance running|middle distance runners]] and [[sprint (running)|sprinters]] at speeds of 6–12 miles per hour (10-19 kilometers per hour).<ref name="Kenney">{{cite book |last1=Kenney |first1=W. Larry |last2=Wilmore |first2=Jack H. |last3=Costill |first3=David L. |title=Physiology of Sport and Exercise |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YHZtv4XKeCMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=May 12, 2012 |edition=5th |series= |volume= |date= May 2011 |origyear=1994 |publisher=Human Kinetics |location=Champaign, Illinois |isbn=978-0-7360-9409-2 |pages=111 |chapter=Energy Expenditure and Fatigue |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=zQGKmbg18J8C&lpg=PP1&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> At those speeds, film analysis has shown that sprinters and middle distance have more vertical motion than marathoners.<ref name="Kenney"/>

